1. ARCHITECTURAL CHOICE: MULTI-AGENT SYSTEM
-------------------------------------------
A Multi-Agent architecture is the most suitable approach for this scenario because:

- Parallel Investigation: Monitoring metrics, deployment logs, and database activity are independent tasks that can be performed simultaneously.
- Specialized Responsibilities: Each agent focuses on a specific infrastructure component, improving efficiency and accuracy.
- Controlled Automation: Remediation actions are executed only after validating confidence levels or obtaining human approval when required.
- Faster Resolution: Running investigations concurrently reduces overall incident response time.

2. WORKFLOW DIAGRAM
-------------------

---------------------------------------------------------
{System Alert Triggered}
        ↓
{Parallelly:
  Agent A - Analyze Monitoring Metrics,
  Agent B - Review Deployment Logs,
  Agent C - Check Database Performance}
        ↓
{Central Orchestrator Collects Findings}
        ↓
{Evaluate Confidence Level}
        ↓
{If Confidence is Low → Human Approval}
        ↓
{Execute Remediation Action
 (Rollback / Restart Service)}
        ↓
{Generate RCA and Notify Team}
---------------------------------------------------------


3. PROCESS STAGES
-----------------

Stage 1 – Parallel Diagnostics
- Multiple agents independently investigate different parts of the infrastructure.

Stage 2 – Centralized Analysis
- Findings from all agents are consolidated to identify the root cause.

Stage 3 – Decision and Remediation
- The system evaluates confidence levels before executing corrective actions.

Stage 4 – Reporting and Communication
- A structured incident report is generated and shared with the operations team.

4. EXPECTED OUTCOME
-------------------
The Multi-Agent design enables faster troubleshooting, improved reliability, controlled automation, and efficient incident resolution while maintaining operational safety.